data.content:
In xUnit, setup/teardown maps to constructor/dispose and `IClassFixture<T>`:

```csharp
// Shared class-level setup/teardown → IClassFixture
public class DatabaseFixture : IAsyncLifetime
{
    public Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    public Task DisposeAsync()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }
}

// Per-test setup → constructor, teardown → IDisposable
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // [SetUp] → constructor (runs before each test)
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // [TearDown] → Dispose (runs after each test)
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + `IAsyncLifetime.InitializeAsync` |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IAsyncLifetime.DisposeAsync` |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(removed — not needed)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

The fixture instance is created once and injected via the constructor parameter. xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/dispose naturally replace per-test setup/teardown.
